text:
NEW VIDEO: Chairman @SenPatRoberts Hears #Cryptocurrency Update from #CFTC Chairman @giancarloCFTC 
https://t.co/DzTQQb6s1G

Roberts: Whether it‚Äôs market participants who rely on the #CFTC to provide regulatory certainty, or consumer financial advocates who highlight the need for robust oversight of the market; I think everyone can agree we need a full panel of commissioners at the CFTC.
Roberts: We will move forward on consideration of the additional vacant #CFTC commissioner spot as soon as an individual is nominated. We need to move forward and get a fully functioning CFTC.

Roberts: Without an additional #CFTC commissioner, finalizing important rules is made much more difficult. We would like Dawn Stump, who was reported out of the committee last year, confirmed as soon as possible. The hold of her pending nomination is unacceptable.
Roberts: We continue to hear from important derivative end-users in the ag sector and beyond, eagerly awaiting resolution to important rule makings mandated under #DoddFrank.

Roberts: We are seeing how the decisions of European officials regarding cross border financial regulations may upend carefully negotiated agreements that would otherwise provide regulatory certainty to financial stakeholders operating on an international stage. #Brexit

Roberts: The technology underlying cryptocurrencies has transformative potential. #Blockchain, or distributed ledger technology, may offer the economy significant benefits as it is used to create more secure, transparent and efficient ways for record keeping.

Roberts: Because #cryptocurrency offerings, and the technologies they are built upon are skyrocketing, regulators like the #CFTC are working hard to provide consumer protection, but without stifling further innovations in the market.

Roberts: This hearing is timely, especially in the derivatives sector where commodities like #Bitcoin & cryptocurrencies, are discussed not only among large financial institutions on Wall Street, but also retail purchasers trying to determine the role cryptocurrencies should play

Roberts: Today, we'll examine issues within the derivatives markets space, including key end-user rules pending before the #CFTC, status of cross border equivalency agreements, and determining the proper role of regulators in the evolving market of cryptocurrencies.
Chairman @SenPatRoberts has gaveled in today's #CFTC oversight hearing. Watch live or later: https://t.co/j5r1168rbB. https://t.co/nXnNd7BeSz

text: VIDEO: Chairman Roberts Emphasizes Importance of Agriculture Security https://t.co/8FyE1aIJ9C

https://t.co/zrEcta2IjT

text: RT @BiodefenseStudy: Key questions: What does risk management look like, where should resources go, and how  should our #agrodefense organi‚Ä¶
retweet_text: Key questions: What does risk management look like, where should resources go, and how  should our #agrodefense organization look like? @SenateAgGOP https://t.co/w0FFOVBl2c

text: Roberts: Today, we'll take stock in where we have come since the early 2000s when the issue of ag security was first visited & discuss where we need to go from here. The Ag Committee last held a hearing on this subject over a decade ago, and significance of this issue has grown.

Roberts: The 2015 Avian Influenza outbreak was unprecedented. While USDA managed through the situation as well as could be expected, it showed how vulnerable the ag sector is to such an event. It‚Äôs made everyone involved begin to think about ways in which we can improve. (2/2)
Roberts: Biological threats, whether naturally occurring, like the avian influenza outbreak of 2015, or intentionally introduced, could pose great harm to our food supply and economy. (1/2)
Roberts: The National Bio and Agro-defense Facility (NBAF) in Manhattan, Kansas, will be a critical part of keeping US agriculture, our food supply, economy, and most important, our people, safe.

Roberts: In 1999, as Chairman of the newly-formed Emerging Threats Subcommittee of the Senate Armed Services Committee, I became aware of the threat our nation faced against intentionally introduced pathogens to be weaponized and aimed at destroying plant and animal populations.

Roberts: Today, we'll hear about an issue of the utmost importance, not only to farmers, ranchers and the ag value chain, but also to consumers, the American economy and the safety of our country. Ag security is a broad reaching issue and involves many govt agencies, beyond USDA.
Chairman @SenPatRoberts has gaveled in today's hearing on agriculture security. Watch live or later: https://t.co/SfxujynnDH. https://t.co/5ySUa2dnIo

retweet_text: Happening now: excellent @WITA_DC discussion on Agriculture, Trade & American Leadership with Ambassador Max Baucus & @SenPatRoberts https://t.co/Ty7tzos0E0

text: RT @WITA_DC: ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre going to do everything we can to provide farmers everything they deserve‚Äù-Chairman Pat Roberts at WITA‚Äôs event on Agric‚Ä¶
retweet_text: ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre going to do everything we can to provide farmers everything they deserve‚Äù-Chairman Pat Roberts at WITA‚Äôs event on Agriculture, Trade and American Leadership

text: Roberts: No one knows more than the agriculture sector about the rewards that come from our trading partners. Agriculture should be front and center as the U.S. pursues trading opportunities around the world.

Roberts: We are at a crossroads on trade. If the U.S. is to continue both as a leader in the global market and to grow the American economy, then we must aggressively work to strengthen existing relationships, and develop new ones. #NAFTA

Roberts: I believe we should be aggressively seeking new agreements and trading opportunities around the world. If the U.S. isn‚Äôt leading the charge and setting the rules, the European Union or others will be.

Roberts: Canada and Mexico have been continuously ranked in the top 5 destinations for U.S. exports since #NAFTA was signed into law. We must work hard to continue to cultivate and grow that mutually beneficial relationship.
Roberts: U.S. ag has grown because of agreements like #NAFTA. From the farmer in the field to the grocer in the store, American workers have benefited from that growth.

Roberts: Trade is more than a product crossing a border. A seed planted in a field ultimately becomes a meal for a family, but in between you‚Äôll find the combine that harvests it, the facility that processes it, and most important the people employed at every step of the way. https://t.co/1LVQwlM2Xe

Roberts: I joined Senator @JohnBoozman & 16 Senators in requesting that before committing to any changes in #NAFTA, the economic analysis illustrating the impact on the full supply chain of industries involved be shared.

Roberts: There's a lot of frustration in farm country because we're missing opportunities to grow our exports. #NAFTA renegotiation could provide just that opportunity. Strengthening and modernizing NAFTA should result in even stronger economic growth for the US, Canada & Mexico.

Roberts: I've been encouraging everyone ‚Äì farmers, ranchers, manufacturers, Senators, Administration officials ‚Äì to fight the pervasive view that our economy has not benefited from #NAFTA. I thank Ambassador Baucus and Senator Lugar for their efforts. https://t.co/zlueuXA4ia
Roberts: I've also heard from folks around the country that they need reliable markets, both domestically and abroad, to sell not just the things that we make, but also the commodities that we grow.

Roberts: In preparation for writing #FarmBill18, I‚Äôve been talking with folks all over the country, and one thing is clear: times are challenging in farm country. We're going to do what we can to provide farmers with certainty they need to be successful producers.

Roberts at @WITA_DC: As the Chairman of the Senate Ag Committee, my primary task is to work on behalf of farmers, ranchers, growers, and other rural stakeholders in Kansas and across the country. https://t.co/BpaDfpXIL3

text: Roberts: Where ag and trade meet, we get results. So, saddle up and ride with me.
Roberts: We successfully confirmed Under Secretary McKinney, and he‚Äôs already leading a delegation to India to expand U.S. ag exports. 2/2
Roberts: In the '14 Farm Bill, we est. a new USDA Trade Under Secretary to focus on opening markets for U.S. agriculture. 1/2
Roberts: We are coming to a crossroads. The decisions made on international trade will determine the future economic success of our country.
Roberts: We are fighting a pervasive view that our economy has not benefited from #NAFTA.
Roberts: I welcome the Administration‚Äôs focus on eliminating long-standing trade barriers US producers & exporters face around the globe.
Roberts: In building relationships with Canada & Mexico, our countries have also integrated markets through value-added products.
Roberts: Mexico barely registered as a market prior to #NAFTA, but it is now the top destination for #Kansas #wheat.
FACT: over the course of #NAFTA, U.S. ag exports have increased to Canada by 265% and to Mexico by 289%.
Roberts: The ongoing negotiation to modernize and strengthen #NAFTA puts us at such a critical juncture in U.S. trade policy.
FACT: Canada & Mexico have continuously been ranked in the top 5 destinations for U.S. ag exports since #NAFTA was signed into law in 1993.
Roberts: Farmers & ranchers need a reliable market domestically & abroad to sell not just things that we make, but also commodities we grow.
Roberts: Low commodity prices are weighing on the farm sector. Farmers and ranchers need whatever certainty we can give.
Roberts: I‚Äôve heard from a broad range of folks & one thing is clear ‚Äì times are challenging in farm country. We're in a rough patch.
Roberts: As the Chairman of the Senate Ag Committee, my task is to work on behalf of farmers, ranchers, growers, and rural stakeholders.

WATCH + READ Chairman @SenPatRoberts's Opening Statement in Today's Conservation, Forestry Hearing 
https://t.co/zXUZEJQKLx #FarmBill18
Roberts: As the Ag Committee writes #FarmBill18, we're in a tough budget environment. I urge everyone to work to protect conservation.
Roberts: While Kansas may not be the most forested state, I understand forestry challenges, which aren't vastly different from ag challenges
Roberts: @SteveDaines & I learned issues facing forestry & land owners, regulatory challenges related to fed land mgmt & endangered species https://t.co/ABV4c6gEjS
Roberts: This hearing is timely, having just visited Big Sky Country with @SteveDaines. #FarmBill18 https://t.co/k3qF7lfjxg
Roberts: I hope we hear input from our witnesses and receive recommendations about how Congress can improve these programs in #FarmBill18.
Roberts: We'll hear from @USDA who administers & delivers conservation & forestry programs, and stakeholders who utilize the programs.
Roberts: Our 2 panels will provide input on current status of programs: what is working well & what challenges remain for #FarmBill18.
Roberts: The Forestry title provided helpful tools for land managers on private, state and federal land part of the National Forest System.
Roberts: The Conservation title contributed to deficit reduction through voluntary cuts to conservation programs totaling $6 BILLION.
Roberts: In the '14 Farm Bill, 23 programs were consolidated into 13 programs w/ sole purpose of improving program efficiencies. #FarmBill18
Roberts: Through voluntary-not regulatory-conservation programs, farmers are making a difference & contributing to environmental benefits.
Roberts: I've heard how these prgms incentivize farmers to take conservation to the next level & the need for continued federal investment.
Roberts: Today, our committee turns its attention to two important titles in the #FarmBill18: Conservation and Forestry.

NEWS RELEASE: Chairman @SenPatRoberts Holds CFTC Chairman Nomination Hearing https://t.co/IXBjwKurAR
Roberts to Giancarlo: Thank you for your commitment to fostering a functional marketplace for all participants, especially rural Americans.
Roberts: Americans would feel the effects if ag producers lacked the market‚Äôs affordable, effective risk mgmt tools to lock in fair prices.
Roberts: It's often lost on Washington that financial markets create stability, esp. when we go to the grocery store & buy affordable food.
Roberts: Commissioners must understand historic nature of a portion of the markets regulated by CFTC-provide risk mgmt tools to ag producers
Roberts: Giancarlo's effort to apply rules/regs in a less burdensome manner is 1 way to get agencies back to intended role-govern, not rule.
Roberts: Congress & federal financial regulators must provide relief to US food and energy providers & exporters. We need a functioning CFTC
Roberts: Yet, when Dodd-Frank became law & the CFTC began writing new regulations, limited flexibility was provided from gov't overreach 2/2
Roberts: During Dodd-Frank, bipartisan members insisted on flexibility for folks who rely on markets & didn't contribute to the crisis. 1/2
Roberts: It was not the farmer, rancher, rural cooperative, electric utility, or end-users who contributed to the financial crisis of '08.
Roberts to Giancarlo: In fact, in 2014, this Committee voted unanimously to advance your nomination & the Senate confirmed you by voice vote
Roberts to Giancarlo: It's essential the CFTC have individuals in charge who take its mission statement to heart. You have demonstrated that
Today's nomination hearing for CFTC Chairman is live: https://t.co/UhTORYbEgH. https://t.co/OVSQQTxHXv
Roberts: CFTC's services allow those who rely on derivatives to hedge commercial risk, focus on innovation, job creation, and production.
Roberts: CFTC's mission is to foster open, transparent, competitive, and financially sound markets, while working to prevent systemic risk
Roberts: Today, we consider the nomination of Mr. Giancarlo to serve as Chairman of the U.S Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).

text:
NEWS RELEASE: Senate Ag Chairman @SenPatRoberts Gathers Perspectives from Farm Economy Experts
https://t.co/QkSCrLNSjz
NEWS RELEASE: Chairman @SenPatRoberts Gathers Perspectives from Farm Economy Experts https://t.co/QkSCrLNSjz #FarmBill18
Roberts: Our role on the Ag Committee is to pass a #FarmBill18 that provides certainty & stability to farmers, ranchers & rural communities
Roberts: We can do 1 of 2 things‚Äîfocus on narrow interests that don‚Äôt serve all of ag, or work together to get things done like in the past.
Roberts: These weather events, on top of the economic conditions, are why we have strong risk management tools available to help producers.
Roberts: Just a couple weeks ago, a blizzard dumped over 20" of snow that has the potential to impact roughly 40% of the wheat acreage in KS
Roberts: Earlier this year, farmers/ranchers from KS, OK, TX & CO experienced devastating wildfires that affected more than 1 million acres.
Roberts: It is essential that small differences do not get in the way of the larger goal ‚Äì to pass #FarmBill18.
Roberts: We need to find ways to reduce regulatory burdens that hurt producers‚Äô bottom lines and strengthen our export markets.
Roberts: We need to ensure producers have risk management tools. Crop insurance is the most valuable tool in the risk management toolbox.
Roberts: We need certainty, bold thinking, and new ideas that address today‚Äôs challenges and these tough times in the agricultural economy.
Roberts: Ag understand fiscal responsibility. But now is not the time for more cuts. We need to review what's working and what's not.
Roberts: '14 Farm Bill voluntarily cut spending. Prev crop insurance contract negotiation cut $6B on top of $6 billion cut in 08 Farm Bill.
Roberts: Over the past few years, global production exceeded global demand- supply & demand are working. Natl debt is nearing $20 trillion
Low commodity prices continue to weigh on farm sector profits: crop receipts expected to decline $42billion+, livestock receipts $23billion+
Roberts: During the 2014 Farm Bill, net farm income was at record highs. In years since, the farm sector is expected to face a 50% decline.
Roberts: Times are challenging right now in farm country, and that‚Äôs why we are here today ‚Äì to examine rural America's economic landscape.
Roberts: We'll continue to listen to farmers, ranchers, lenders, co-ops, etc. on what‚Äôs working/not working/improvements in the Farm Bill.
Tune into today's farm economy hearing, LIVE now: https://t.co/j5r1168rbB. https://t.co/D7iOLqYy8r
Roberts: We started off this year by holding 2 #FarmBill18 hearings at @KState & @michiganstateu to do one thing - listen.
Be sure to tune into today's Senate Ag hearing on the farm economy. Watch LIVE at 10am EDT: https://t.co/j5r1168rbB. #FarmBill18 https://t.co/qIfuRiDnIj

text: Roberts: We need to grow more with fewer resources. It takes the govt providing an adequate safety net & then getting out of producers' way.
Roberts: Feeding the world is an ag & national security challenge. Show me a country that cannot feed itself-I‚Äôll show you a nation in chaos
Roberts: Feeding 9 billion people requires efficiency, not just on the farm and ranch, but also ‚Äì and most certainly ‚Äì in the government.
Roberts: Global population is rapidly approaching 9 BILLION people. Ag production will need to double in the near future to meet demand.
Roberts: We must be judicious w/ scarce resources, ensure programs accomplish their fundamental purposes, examine programs for effectiveness
Roberts: Agriculture, esp the Farm Bill, consistently answers the call to do more with less. The last Farm Bill voluntarily cut spending.
.@SenPatRoberts: To those who say passing #FarmBill18 in this environment is a daunting task, I say together we can get it done.
Roberts: @SenStabenow and I are working to make Washington understand differences b/n economic conditions then and what ag is facing now.
Roberts: All of ag is struggling. During the last Farm Bill debate, ag enjoyed high prices. Now we face years of low prices across the board
Roberts: Passing a Farm Bill won‚Äôt be easy, so we need your help to write a bill that meets needs of producers across all regions, all crops
Roberts: Producers, agribiz, rural Americans sign up for programs, comply with regs, & feel the pain of burdensome or unsupportive policies.
Roberts: It's important to get out of DC & hear directly from folks about Farm Bill where it matters: farms/ranches, businesses, communities
Roberts: Producers in MI stepped up, raising private funds,sending hay and materials to rebuild. Kansans are extremely grateful. (2/2)
In March, KS farmers, ranchers were hit by wildfire, losing homes, cattle, facilities, fencing and livelihoods, but not their futures (1/2)

text: Chairman @SenPatRoberts Thanks Vilsack, Questions Administration‚Äôs Overregulation and Uncertainty in Farm Economy https://t.co/gh6h5BcuvU
Roberts: Mr. Secretary, you‚Äôve filled that role on many occasions, over last 7+ yrs. I ask you to finish your term with the same mindset.
Roberts: Today I find myself asking for what I asked for in 2009, a champion, spokesperson, educator who will stand up for production #ag.
Roberts: This Administration is moving forward with regs across all sectors that will knowingly cut margins, hurting producers and consumers
.@SenPatRoberts: During these tough economic times farmers, ranchers, and agri-businesses compete at the thinnest of profit margins.
Roberts: Our producers fought drought, floods, fires, disease, etc. That‚Äôs what farmers do-they take on Mother Nature‚Äôs worst & plow forward
Roberts: Farm country has experienced a roller coaster since 2009. Our producers have seen historic high prices and now historic lows.
Roberts: With large global inventories for wheat, corn, dairy, etc, the prices farmers receive may stay relatively low for several years.
.@SenPatRoberts: The downturn in the #ag economy is taking a toll on farmers and ranchers' wallets and the health of many family farms.
Roberts: I attended the Kansas State Fair, where I heard first-hand what farmers have on their minds. Plain & simple, they're worried.
.@SenPatRoberts: Today‚Äôs hearing is an opportunity for us all to address the economic concerns we hear rising from farm country.
.@SenPatRoberts: It was January 2009 when Secretary Vilsack testified before this committee for the 1st time.
Roberts: Today, Sec Vilsack, the administration‚Äôs longest serving cabinet member, is here to give his final testimony in this historic room.

text: .@SenPatRoberts:  The CFTC must look through the lens of regulatory practicality - not the lens of regulatory irrationality.
Roberts: Congress should not withhold needed regulatory relief for farmers, risk management service providers any longer-nor should the CFTC
Roberts: This Cmte passed the Commodity End-User Relief Act, providing regulatory certainty to end-users & increasing customer protections.
Roberts: We hear concerns from constituents who describe in detail the regulatory overreach stemming from the implementation of Dodd-Frank
Roberts: It was not the farmer, rancher, producer, or commercial end-user that caused the financial crisis of 2008, yet they pay the price.
Roberts: Producers, end-users, municipalities, etc use markets to lock in a price & produce goods/services for the economy & create jobs.
.@SenPatRoberts: There are 2 Commissioner vacancies at the @CFTC, and that is what brings us here today.
Roberts: To fulfill its mission, CFTC is comprised of 5 Commissioners nominated by the President, with the advice and consent of the Senate.
.@SenPatRoberts: The CFTC is charged w/ fostering open, transparent, competitive, & financially sound markets, while avoiding systemic risk.
.@SenPatRoberts: Today we consider the nominations of Dr. Christopher Brummer and Brian Quintenz to serve as Commissioners of the @CFTC.

https://t.co/FetQ3I6xPR https://t.co/JeZxk9ZQyo
Roberts: Forestry, like production ag, faces challenges - over regulation, frivolous litigation, admin obstacles stalling fed agency action.
Roberts: Complexity is no reason for inaction. I'm committed to work w/ colleagues to get this wildfire legislation across the finish line
Roberts: This amdt contains policies that reduce admin burdens to the Forest Service & lend efficiencies for collaborative forest management
Clear msg at Nov hearing: Congress must address wildfire funding, fed land managers need ability to manage forest landscapes to be resilient
Roberts: The last significant standalone forestry legislation we considered was the Healthy Forests Restoration Act 13 yrs ago (now is law)
Roberts: This summer I introduced S. 3085, the Emergency Wildfire & Forest Management Act of 2016, which was referred to this Committee
Roberts: The Senate #Ag Committee has been referred the Resilient Federal Forests Act, which the House passed on a bipartisan basis in 2015.
.@SenPatRoberts: The Forest Service funding decision will be determined with the Committees of jurisdiction and at a later point.
Roberts: The wildfire issue is a complex issue that involves several cmtes of jurisdiction - specifically w/ the Forest Service funding fix.
Roberts: HR2647 addresses wildfire funding & provides tools to address systemic problems contributing to the degradation of public lands.
Roberts: Coming off another troubling wildfire season, today‚Äôs markup is a critical moment to work towards a solution addressing wildfires.

text: Chairman @SenPatRoberts: Sales of cattle, hogs, poultry & eggs also accounted for $141 billion annually. Those are impressive numbers.
Roberts: According to USDA's #ag census, beef, pork & poultry sectors account for 36% of total ag sales on an annual basis. That # is rising
.@SenPatRoberts: #Kansas ranks 3rd in #beef production & is growing in #pork production, a boon to many of our small, rural communities.
Roberts: East KS is known for rolling Flint Hills, spotted w/ grazing cattle. West KS has some of the largest, most modern beef feedlots.
Roberts: I'm confident that through challenges, animal ag will lead the world in delivering safe, affordable meat products to consumers.
Roberts: This demonstrates how savvy today‚Äôs farmers & ranchers must be. This is a livelihood not for the risk averse or faint of heart.
Roberts: When you realize the ‚Äúgood-times‚Äù are composed of margins of a few cents/dollars per animal, you understand how tough business is
Roberts: Unfortunately we know there has been significant erosion in farm equity due to these disease outbreaks and marketplace volatility.
Roberts: Other events, like diseases that ravaged the egg, pork & turkey sectors, can leave producers with little to no income for months.
Roberts: One year they may receive record prices for their animals and the next see a dramatic drop in value, like in the beef sector.
Chairman @SenPatRoberts: Today‚Äôs livestock and poultry producers are operating in a highly cyclical marketplace.
Roberts: While US livestock & poultry sectors weather ebbs and flows every day, recent years have seen greater volatility & unpredictability
Chairman @SenPatRoberts: It‚Äôs been 5 years since our last Committee hearing on the state of the livestock and poultry sectors.
Roberts: Farmers &  ranchers are here to give us perspectives on marketplace opportunities and challenges in the livestock & poultry sectors
Be sure to tune into today's livestock and poultry hearing at 10am Eastern. Watch live: https://t.co/j5r1168rbB.

text: .@SenPatRoberts: I remember the difficult times for the farm economy during the 1980s. No one wants to see a repeat of those dark days.
Roberts: Congress established the Farm Credit System 100 yrs ago. Providing farmers accessible, affordable credit remains important today
Roberts: The Farm Service Agency has seen a 21% increase in farm loans since last year-a troubling indication of a struggling ag economy.
.@SenPatRoberts: The Farm Credit Administration, an independent agency comprised of a 3-member board, regulates the Farm Credit System.
RT @agripulse: Farm Credit hearing kicks off at @SenateAgGOP. Two panels of witnesses to look at farm economy, lending practices. https://t‚Ä¶
retweet_text: Farm Credit hearing kicks off at @SenateAgGOP. Two panels of witnesses to look at farm economy, lending practices. https://t.co/PtEd55ktYq

text:
Roberts:Farm Credit System is comprised of 74 Ag Credit Associations & 4 regional
banks, which provide Associations w/ funds to make loans

Roberts: Farm Credit System compromised of privately owned cooperative lenders to
provide rural borrowers w/ permanent/affordable credit
.@SenPatRoberts: Rural America relies on a network of credit providers consisting of the private sector and the Farm Credit System.

Roberts: Today‚Äôs discussion is timely. It has been almost 10 yrs since banking industry
or Farm Credit System testified before the cmte

Roberts: Lenders note more farmers carry over outstanding debt from previous yrs, w
increased demand for loans & weakening repayment rates
Roberts: K-State Dept of Ag Econ Ag Lender Survey expects credit environment for farmers to remain difficult for at least a few more yrs

Roberts: As our farmers deal with low commodity prices & elevated input costs,
access to affordable credit is as important today as ever.
.@SenPatRoberts : Over the past three years alone, net farm income is expected to decline by 56 percent.

Roberts:Farmers are experiencing difficult economic conditions as farm sector
profitability is forecast to decline for a 3rd straight year
Roberts: We'll examine whether the Farm Credit Administration is exercising appropriate oversight of the Farm Credit System.

Roberts: We'll examine credit in rural America, health of ag lending & impacts of
current credit environment on our nation‚Äôs farmers.
Don't forget to watch today's Farm Credit hearing at 10:15am Eastern. Watch live: https://t.co/j5r115QPN1. https://t.co/FHiszRcYtG

text: Roberts: We should not withhold needed regulatory relief for our farmers, ranchers & risk management service providers any longer.
Roberts: The Chairman's mark addresses regulatory overreach and provides clarity & relief, as well as puts in place customer protections.
Roberts: Or do you support unnecessary and over burdensome regulation? That‚Äôs a pretty simple answer, folks. 3/3
Roberts: Do you want to stand up for those who put food on our table, affordable gas in our cars, & provide electricity to our homes? 2/3
Roberts: Do you want to fight for the wheat farmer trying to lock in a favorable price for his crop with his local grain elevator? 1/3
Roberts: Rural America did not contribute to the '08 financial crisis, so why have they been regulated as if they were part of the problem?
Roberts: Congress created the Dodd-Frank mandate to regulate speculators & investors - NOT to regulate true hedgers in the market.
Roberts: It's our duty to make it easier for ‚Äúon the ground‚Äù participants to hedge/protect themselves, especially with market volatility.
Roberts: A grain elevator needs to be able to hedge inventory received when markets are closed to provide the best price to the farmer.
Roberts: The Commodity End-User Relief Act is a compromise that provides regulatory certainly to end-users, increases customer protections.
Roberts: It has been 8 years since the crisis, 6 years since bill passage, & there has been no action from this Cmte. Today, that changes.
Roberts: Yet when Dodd-Frank became law, and the CFTC began writing new regulations, it was rural America who was over-regulated.
Roberts: Congress rxn to '08 financial crisis led to regulatory change. Many raised concerns that legislation may hurt folks not at fault.
Roberts: look at volatility in corn prices. A few years ago: >$7/bushel. Now <$4. I aim to help producers & those up/down the market chain
Roberts: As the futures & derivatives markets have grown to incl producers' input costs, so too has the producers' risk management toolbox.
Roberts: End-users are market participants, incl farmers/ranchers, biz & co-ops, who use derivatives & futures contracts to manage risks.
Roberts: First, we need to examine who we are working to help and why they need our help -- end-users.
Roberts: It's a historic day for the Committee, as the last time we held a markup to reauthorize the #CFTC was 10+ yrs ago. It‚Äôs time to act

text: Roberts: I'm confident-even w/ today‚Äôs challenges-farmers will continue to deliver safe, affordable & abundant products to our dinner tables
Roberts: U.S. #ag has a long history of providing the safest, most abundant food supply in the world b/c our producers‚Äô strength, dedication
Roberts: It is critical that we take the lessons learned from this #HPAI outbreak and put them to good use.
Roberts: US biz upstream (food producers/restaurant owners) want to ensure disease threats don‚Äôt continue causing extreme price volatility.
Roberts: #HPAI has resulted in depopulation of 10% of egg-laying hens and 3% of turkeys produced in the U.S.
Roberts: We need to identify improvements to be made to national animal health infrastructure and biosecurity measures on farms. #HPAI
Roberts: It is critical we hear lessons learned from the impacted industries and from the animal health experts at USDA. #HPAI
Roberts: #Ag businesses are often the backbones of rural communities, and the ripple effect #HPAI has had is dramatic & widespread.
Roberts: Many of the #HPAI-impacted farms employ dozens, or in some cases, hundreds of people.
Roberts: #Ag is a high risk biz. Poultry & egg producers are experiencing firsthand the damaging toll these risks take on their operations.
Roberts: As we will hear from experts, I emphasize that this outbreak of #HPAI poses no food safety risks, nor any public health risks.
Roberts: Many of the first farms hit with #HPAI have begun repopulating flocks. This is critical so farms to begin generating incoming again

text: Roberts: Our budgetary constraints are real. Our responsibility to our constituents includes not spending money that we don‚Äôt have.

Roberts: It is vital this legislation does not contain additional spending without an offset.
Roberts: Child nutrition programs have historically had strong bipartisan support. 2004, 2010 reauthorizations passed by unanimous consent
Roberts: Working together, we can preserve the nutritional quality of school meals w/o one-size-fits-all approach that prevents flexibility.

Roberts: In the school meal programs, there are significant error rates & improper payment levels, highlighted in reports from USDA OIG, GAO

Roberts: It is time for folks to come together and be a part of crafting legislation, not to stand outside the process, hoping it fails.

Roberts: Not every prgm needs an overhaul, but every federal prgm can benefit from increased efficiency, improved integrity, waste reduction

Roberts: I hope #Cuba will embrace the practices of free trade, enterprise & commerce, so both countries gain from increased relations.
Roberts: #Ag has long been used as a tool, not a weapon, for peace and stability.
Roberts: Like myself, many of our witnesses here have traveled to #Cuba to see first-hand what challenges and opportunities exist.
Roberts: We will hear from experts, from regulators who write policies toward Cuba to producers who grow the market for their products.
Roberts: Foreign policy doesn't happen in a vacuum. We have to work out a plan towards lifting the embargo. This should include Congress.
Roberts: It is my hope that in the future, the President will work with Congress to determine the best path forward.
Roberts: The decisions that are made regarding increased #trade with #Cuba must be made carefully.
Roberts: I fought to eliminate trade barriers & believe we should continue to work towards new market access opps for US #ag products.
Roberts: International #trade of American #ag products is critical to the nation‚Äôs economy and to our #Kansas farmers & ranchers. #Cuba
Roberts: #TPA is good for #ag, and I look forward to getting it passed. #Cuba
Roberts: Tomorrow @GOPSenFinance will mark up a Trade Promotion Authority bill allowing negotiators to garner the best deal for US exporters
Roberts: At the beginning of this Congress, I was hopeful #trade would be one area where we could work across the aisle. I am still hopeful.
